\section{Introduction}
General relativity, based on the Einstein-Hilbert action, provides a
highly successful classical description of gravitational phenomena
from sub-millimeter to cosmic scales. A central puzzle for the
construction of a consistent quantum theory of gravity is its
perturbative nonrenormalizability. This is manifested by the fact,
that an expansion in terms of
Newton's constant about flat spacetime
gives rise to a divergence at two-loop order. This spoils meaningful
predictions for $S$-matrix elements, unless a Goroff-Sagnotti
counter-term of the form
